 .
 Moreover, we would also like to classify the job listings according to
 the location of the position, and the branch or industry it falls into.
 As seen is figure 1, this information is not available when looking at
 each job listing individually.
 However, Jobindex allows you to filter the results according to date, job
 category and geographical area which meant that we had to scrape the search
 results of all the possible combinations between location, area and remote
 keyword for the period 2010-2010.
 The job categories used by Jobindex are Information Technology, Engineering
 and Technology, Management and Staff, Trade and Service, Industry and Craft,
 Sales and Communication, Teaching, Office and Finance, Social and Health
 and Other positions and more specific subcategories.
 Moreover, the geographical which we will include in our data are: Capital
 Area, North Zealand, Region Zealand, Funen, North Jutland, Central Jutland,
 Sotuh Jutland, Bornholm and Denmark
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have excluded Greenland, Faroe Islands, and Foregin countries.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lastly, to put the development in remote job listings into perspective,
 we will also need data for the total monthly job listings for the period
 2010-2020 across categories and geographical areas.
 For this we change the search filters accordingly and scrape the total
 number of jobs that match our search.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Data cleansing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the categories and locations provided in Jobindex's search filters
 are not mutually exclusive, and neither are the remote keywords that we
 defined, our dataset is bound to have many duplicates.
 We start with a dataset containing 54281 joblistings and we progressively
 delete duplicate job listings.
 The step-by-step process can be found in Figure 2.
 Notice that the way we have cleaned our data has the implication that if
 the same job falls under two (or more) categories, by deleting its duplicates
 we are randomly assigning one of the two categories and deleting the other
 one.
 Although this isn't ideal, it is the best solution we could come up with.
 After these steps, we end up with a dataset consisting of 14717 job listings
 in the period 2010-2020 where at least one of our remote keywords was mentioned.
\end_layout

