\begin_layout Section*
Forecasting as a COVID-19 counterfactual
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will do two things
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 What would it have looked like if it wasnt for COVID 19
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Now that COVID has happened what can we expect for the future
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As social scientists, we are often interested in estimating the treatment
 effect that different exogenous shocks such as policy changes can have
 on different variables on interest.
 Although the development in remote job listings for 2020 doesn't particularly
 stand out when compared to the rest of the sample, it is reasonable to
 believe[INSERT SOME SOURCE] that the oubreak of the pandemic has forced
 businesses to change the way they operate in order to adapt to the environment
 of uncertainty regarding their employees' mobility.
 In this case, the mobility restrictions imposed by governments' can be
 seen as an exogenous shock to the remote labour market and it is worth
 questioning what the magnitude of the effect of this shock is.
 Ideally, we would like to observe our outcome (remote job listings) in
 both state of the worlds, that is, both with and without the presence of
 COVID-19.
 Although this is impossible, fitting a model using data for the period
 prior to the pandemic and making a forecast for 2020 could provide us with
 an artificial counterfactual to the actual development of remote job listings.
 Notice that the purpose of this exercise is not to formally estimate the
 true causal effect of COVID-19 on remote work, but rather to motivate and
 challenge future research into the potential that policy changes have on
 rearranging the incentives in the labour market.
 Since we have univariate time series data, for our forecasting we chose
 to use the Prophet algorithm developed by Facebook since it is considered
 to perform well in modelling data with seasonal effects
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and shifts in trends.Part of the attractiveness of Prophet is that it automatica
lly finds seasonal trends beneath the data and offers a set of parameters
 that are easy to understand and can be calibrated accordingly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the many hidden secrets that is not so obvious when first using Prophet
 is that it has a built-in cross validation function.
 This function will take your data and train the model on a period you specify.
 It will then predict a period that you also specify.
 Prophet will then train your data on a bigger period, then predict again
 and this will repeat until the end point is reached.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Prophet :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Linear growth
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bayesian based curve fitting method to forecast the time series data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
built-in cross validation function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the many hidden secrets that is not so obvious when first using Prophet
 is that it has a built-in cross validation function.
 This function will take your data and train the model on a period you specify.
 It will then predict a period that you also specify.
 Prophet will then train your data on a bigger period, then predict again
 and this will repeat until the end point is reached.
\end_layout

